Mar 11 2007 	Great Location	The best thing about this hotel is the location. It is literally minutes from the very touristy Fishermans Wharf and is even closer to bus and cable car stops. There is nothing flash about the hotel but it does provide a quiet, relaxed base from which to explore San Francisco.The room I had was spotlessly clean and was a decent size although the bathroom was a little compact. Having said that, the room had everything needed for your stay. In room safe, tea/coffee, hair dryer, iron, etc were all included free of charge. The huge bed was comfortable and provided a sound nights sleep.Breakfast was disappointing. The continental selection was small and the only warm food available was an apple cake. It wasn't bad, just that I prefer a cooked breakfast, or at least the option of one.There is a small fitness room in the hotel with six or seven exercise machines available free of charge.The hotel has no bar but the one directly across the street (knuckles) is excellent and I'd recommend the BBQ pizza which is big enough for two and only costs $13.The Holiday Inn Express is designed for the customer who only uses the hotel for sleep and rest and they have got the balance just right. It is a perfect base to explore San Francisco and have a restful nights sleep after all that hill walking.I would use this hotel again	
Feb 23 2007 	Good location average hotel	The best thing about this hotel is the location. It's in easy walking distance to Fishermans Wharf which is where most of the touristy stuff goes on. We did venture into downtown SF, but felt a lot more threatened there than at fishermans Wharf. The hotel itself is quite bland, but clean and comfortable. If you are not planning on spending a lot of time on your room then this is fine. But whilst we were there it poured with rain most of the time, and we found the room quite small when we were trying to dry out our soggy clothes. In this hotel we also got a complimentary breakfast which was a good variety, and a good start to the day. We dont like to get up too early when on holiday so the fact that the breakfast was available until 9.30 was a plus for us! I knew SF was hilly, but they still surprised me - and thank god for the cable cars and trams!! We had a great time here, but mainly becauise we were out and about rather than because the hotel was great. The hotel is basic and functional - clean and the breakfast was good, and a convenient location, but otherwise I dont think we would stay here again. Mainly because we like to stay in different places each time, but also because the room was smaller than we had hoped, and that it just seemed very bland.	
Feb 22 2007	Great and Ideal	I travel the world as an Flight Attendent and always stay at 5 star hotels so when i went on vacation i stayed at the Holiday Inn Express, Fishermans Wharf. It is situated in a fantastic location, near to all the piers and all transport to different parts of the city. The room was very clean and daily cleaned to a high standard. reception staff were extremely helpful and nothing was too much trouble, especially funny was Brandy. The fitness centre was adequate for its purpose and the free internet was a bonus. Free complimentary was nice but you have to be early but then again who wants to eat every morning when there is so much choice in the big city. Overall i thought the hotel and amenities in and close to the hotel was fantastic.	
Jan 31 2007	If the beds were any harder you would be camping	With improvements this hotel has the potential to be great, without them though we would rate it as average.Firstly, this hotel has extremely hard beds even with the extra mattress pad that they provide. If there is one thing you do in San Francisco is a lot of walking and a good nights comfortable sleep is an important factor.When we crawled into bed the first night we noticed how hard the mattress was. I was trying to get comfortable and my arm rubbed over the blanket. To my dismay I felt crusty areas on the blanket as it rubbed against my arm. Without getting into specifics you can guess why the blanket had crusty stains on it and was not clean, it even had a few dirt marks on it too. We stripped the blanket off the bed and we saw that there was a spare blanket in the closet, so we used that one instead.The next day, we reported the dirty blanket to the front desk, along with our TV having a continous buzzing noise too. The gal at the front desk said she would have to talk to the manager about the situation. When I spoke to the manager, she said she told the maid to check the sheets and they were clean. I told her it was not the sheets, but the blanket. She had an odd reaction (sort of like disbelief) she said, &quot;this has never happened here before.&quot; To which I replied, &quot;we travel all over the world and believe me this has never happened to us either.&quot; The manager also mentioned that the blankets are not washed on the same wash cycle as the sheets. She said, she would investigate the blanket problem and adjust our room rate for that night. Which ended up being a few dollars off the nightly room rate. We were moved to another room.The new room was clean, there was no problem with the bedding. We asked for an extra mattress pad to be put on the bed, this made the bed more comfortable to sleep on. Had it not been for the two mattress pads on the bed, we would have found the bed too hard and uncomfortable to sleep on and would have checked out, to find another hotel with a more comfortable bed.The coffee maker in the room is on the bathroom counter right beside a high powered flushing toilet. This is not sanitary considering the splashes from the toilet so close by. We washed the coffee maker out with hot water and soap and moved it to the desk by the TV. I'm not sure why they are not placed there in the first place, as there is plenty of room on the desk beside the TV. The coffee supplied in your room is very weak. I think the coffee supplied is for 2 cups, not for 4 cups. If your making a full pot use both packages of coffee, then it will taste a lot better.The maid service was very efficient, although they start at 8:30am, so if you want to sleep in you should put the &quot;do not disturb&quot; sign on the door. Rush hour starts at 6:00am, so if you are a light sleeper and wake up to traffic, bus and cable car noise, ask for a room facing the courtyard. It has no view, but these rooms are quieter than the street side. There are two computers in the lobby that offer free internet, but a lot of times they are busy in the mornings. We found that the computers had better availability in the afternoons and evenings.The complementary continental breakfast is served from 6:30am to 9:30am. This consists of cold boiled eggs, bran muffins, chocolate muffins, apple muffins, croissants, white &amp; brown bread, english muffins (toasters are available for toasting bread) butter and jam. Plain donuts, chocolate donuts, cinnamon buns, raisin bran cereal, cornflakes cereal, fruit loops cereal, (skim, 2%, homo milk) orange, apple, cranberry juice, coffee, tea, plus fresh fruit - apples, bananas &amp; oranges. The breakfast lull is about around 7:30am to about 8:15am. It is much busier earlier and later. The hotel is conveniently located walking distance to Pier 39. Cable cars, street cars, bus stops are close by. The cab ride from the airport to the hotel costs about $42.00. The parking rate at the hotel is $35.00 per day. We decided to forego the rental car and parking fee. We did not regret this decision as the bus service is very efficient, we only waited 5 minutes for a bus on any given day including Sunday. 15 minutes at the most for a cable car or street car. At the end of the cable car stations in a booth you can purchase a one day Municipal Transit pass (Muni) good for all buses, cable cars and street cars for $11.00. A three day pass costs $18.00 and a 7 day pass costs $24.00. The passes are excellent value, as a one way cable car ride costs $5.00 and you can not hop on and off either. $5.00 for each ride period. There are two supermarkets located close to the hotel. Safeway and Trader Joe's. We found Trader Joes brand sparkling fruit juices able to hold their fizz the next day, as there is no fridge in your hotel room. The plus they taste good too. Walgreens and Cost Plus World market are near by also, but have a more limited food selections. Other retail shops/malls open @ 10:00am. We found that souveniers are cheaper closer to the hotel and China Town then at Pier 39. Ghiradelli square is under renovations until Spring 2007 and Fall 2007 so only about 1/4 of the shops are open there. The second last night of our trip, teenagers were partying with a loud boombox next door @ 2:00am. Security reacted swiftly and put an end to the loud party immediately.	
Jan 30 2007	worth a visit	We spent two week in California, touring, staying in 5 different hotels, and this one was one of the cheaper ones, but just as nice. The rooms were clean and large enough for a family of 4, we had the option of free breakfast each morning with coffee and oj it was basic but nice. the hotel is close to lots of main attractions - our son is in a wheelchair and we had no problems getting around. The only down side was having to pay $20.00 per day to park the car, and should you want food or a beer you have have to go to the hotel next door - a bit of a pain, but there are lots of places to eat near by, the sports bar across the road served food and it was great. THIS HOTEL IS GREAT VALUE FOR MONEY AND IS WELL WORTH A VISIT, we would go back. GIVE IT A GO.	
Jan 3 2007 	Comfortable and convenient	The room was comfortable and warm, the bathroom clean and there were two queen size beds which gave me one of the better sleeps of the holiday (having been round the World, this was the last stage of the tour). The hotel is convenient to the Hyde Street cable car (get there early to avoid the queue) but there is also a lesser known route at the bottom of Taylor Street and it is also worth getting a ride on the old street cars which start in Leavenworth Street. All are within a couple of blocks of the hotel. It is also pleasant to walk through Fort Mason and along the waterfront. And, of course, it is convenient for boats to Alcatraz and Sausalito. Breakfast at the hotel is free but it is also a free-for-all. Everything is disposable - cups, plates, cutlery - so wasteful. The healthy stuff consists of cereal, apples, oranges or bananas and hard boiled egg but if you want muffins, cakes, pastries, donuts, chocolate donuts, etc etc, then this is the place to be. The breakfast room was busy, typically plates were being overfilled and discarded when eyes proved bigger than tummies, and it was far from the quiet, laid back, relaxed breakfast that I enjoy. After a couple of days we gave up on it and went to Starbucks or one of the cafs up the road.There is no restaurant at the hotel but you can use the facilities of the Holiday Inn next door. Pier 39 has some restaurants but they are expensive and have a captive market. Likewise, Fisherman's Wharf itself. We caught the cable car up to Chinatown a couple of times - very good quality and very good value food - and walked back, or we walked up Columbus Avenue to Little Italy where we also got good value meals. Walking at night is OK as there are usually loads of people around, but in some of the streets around the hotel there are down and outs sleeping in doorways but they were asleep and did not give us any hassle.One welcome advantage was the free Internet access in the lobby. I have stayed in other hotels in Fisherman's Wharf and found that this one offered a similar room at a lesser price than some of the others.	
