Aug 1 2006 	Great Location!	We spent a wonderful weekend in San Francisco and stayed one night at the Holiday Inn Express (this hotel does not allow pets, the writer below confused it with the Holiday Inn which is older and does allow them). This property is new and spotlessly clean. We paid extra for a suite and our view was amazing. From our room we could see Alcatraz and part of the Bay. You are walking distance from everything at the Wharf and it is great to be so close (even for bathroom breaks). The parking is $32 but we rode the ferry from Vallejo and parked our van for free there. It was a great trip and I highly recommend it. The hotel may not be the fanciest but you can't beat the location and the price is about the best at the Wharf. The staff at the front desk were very friendly . The breakfast bar was great with a decent variety of food and of course those awesome Holiday Inn Express Cinnamon Rolls!	
Jul 30 2006 	A good place to stay...	Arrived July 23rd for a three night stay and overall we were very satisfied with our stay. We wanted lodging within walking distance to Fisherman's Wharf/Pier 39 and selected the Holiday Inn Express and reading generally favorable reviews on this site. The location is great, convenient to the Wharf, Pier, Bay &amp; Alcatraz Tours, Ghiradelli Square, the Cannery, and the Cable Car line. The hotel does not have a pool or a restaurant but you can use the pool at the adjacant Holiday Inn, where there is also a Denny's Restaurant located.The hotel serves a continental breakfast in the lobby starting at 6:30 AM, consisting of cereal, fruit, pastries, hardboiled eggs, breads and a variety of beverages. We felt the selection was great, but don't sleep in late and expect to be able to eat because it closes at 9:30 AM.The stairs were hard to find and the elevators as slow as any we've ever been on, also the bathroom fan was rather noisy, but the room was clean and adequate for our needs.Aside from the rather high $32 daily parking fee, we felt the hotel was well worth the $110 nightly rate. We would definately stay here again.	
Jul 21 2006 	Ideal Place to Experience SF at the right price	I had looked into what hotel would best suit our needs in San Francisco for several months and decided on the Holiday Inn Express due to a combination of Location, Price, inclusion of buffet breakfast &amp; age of the actual property. With all this in mind me and my girlfriend were satisfied with our stay, not jumping for joy but happy.The location is great for the Wharf. There are around a dozen large hotel-chain properties all situated within an area of a few blocks so whether you stay at the HI Express, Sheraton, Hyatt, etc etc you'll more or less be staying in the same area. The main drawback is that the location is two blocks back from the Wharf area and the immediate vicinity isn't exactly a pleasant one. Pier 39 is a great place for a stroll, grab a meal and browse the shops. The area around the Cannery, Ghiradelli Square &amp; the Cable-Car turnaround is also nice. It's the few blocks in between these areas however that make the Wharf un-savoury. A concentration of very tacky souvenir stores and one-too-many colourful characters spoil the area although we still felt happy that we'd chose the Wharf as our base. We were originally planning a stay at the Westin on Union Square and whilst we saw that the hotel itself was very grand we weren't convinced that staying smack-bang in the centre of the city would have been a better option. Every one of the 4 days we spent in the city involved starting things off within ten minutes of our hotel - whether it be Alcatraz, a superb city tour or cycling over the GG Bridge. The major gripe we had with the area was how early everything closed on Pier 39. We expected to be able to browse the shops, etc after dinner each night but from 10pm onwards the whole area closes up and you're left with the choice of having a drink in one of the few restaurant bars or returning to your hotel.The hotel itself is very modern and spotlessly clean. Certainly no character and most of the rooms face into central courtyards but if it's a new hotel with good standards that you look for this hotel is ideal. The rooms weren't large but fine, especially for a city hotel and the shower, room temperature, furniture etc were all great, as was the buffet breakfast included in the price.All-in-all our 4 days in San Francisco were brilliant, taking in some memorable experiences. If you want a very clean, modern hotel and can get a good rate at the Holiday Inn Express I'd recommend staying here and using it as a base.NB - Some people mix up the adjacent Holiday Inn with the Express - the normal HI is a lot older and I'd definitely opt for the Express over it. We did like the look of the Sheraton however although all the hotels were similar in the area.	
Jul 19 2006 	Typical Holiday Inn	We spend 5 days at the hotel. We selected it because it was dog friendly and reasonably priced for the area. The staff are inconsistent - some were great, others need to get another job. The facilities are older but good, but the beds are rock hard and the pillows about the same - after 5 days, needed a chiropractor. Its a good location for dogs because of the small park next door, but beware the homeless who sleep there. Most ignored us, but some were persistent until we walked off. Its a good jump off for the trolley and a great walk through the Fort, etc. But it is cold! We live at the top of a mountain in Colorado, but this is a piercing cold amplified by the wind and the fog. Plenty of restaurants, but all priced to take your last dollar.. do try Boudin's though - good combination of service, food, and cost.	
